title: Digital Access and Its Influence on Public Health Policy in the U.S.
author: Author Y. Z.
summary: This research investigates the relationship between digital access and public health outcomes in the U.S. The study draws on data from national health surveys and government statistics to analyze patterns of impact. Findings indicate that fluctuations in digital access are statistically correlated with shifts in health outcomes such as mortality, access to preventive care, and disease burden.

statistical_analysis.findings: The analysis revealed a significant association (p < 0.01) between digital access and increased hospital admissions. Counties in the top quintile for digital access had on average a 14.3% higher rate of chronic illness reporting compared to the national median. Education level and access to care were found to moderate this relationship in urban regions.

policy_implication: Policy recommendations include increasing funding to address digital access at the state level. Data supports the introduction of community-based interventions and targeted subsidies to mitigate public health disparities.
references: Digital Access and Public Health Outcomes: A Review. AJPH, 2021.
CDC Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS)
U.S. Census Bureau Public Health Reports
